---
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';

const faqs = [
  { q: 'How do I convert audio to text for free?', a: 'Use Google Docs Voice Typing (free, built-in), YouTube auto-captions, or free tiers of tools like Otter.ai or Whisper (open-source). For shorter audio, Google Docs Voice Typing is the fastest no-cost option.' },
  { q: 'What is the most accurate free audio to text tool?', a: 'OpenAI Whisper is considered the most accurate free transcription model. It is open-source and runs locally. For a no-install option, Otter.ai offers a free tier with good accuracy.' },
  { q: 'Can Google Docs convert audio to text?', a: 'Yes. Google Docs has a built-in Voice Typing feature (Tools → Voice Typing) that transcribes speech from your microphone in real time. It is free and reasonably accurate for clear speech.' },
  { q: 'How do I transcribe a video or audio file to text?', a: 'Upload the file to YouTube as unlisted and use YouTube\'s auto-captions. Or use a free tool like Otter.ai (upload audio) or run OpenAI Whisper locally on your computer.' },
  { q: 'Is there an offline audio to text tool?', a: 'Yes. OpenAI Whisper is a free, open-source transcription model that runs entirely offline on your computer. It supports 99 languages and works with audio and video files.' },
];
---

<BlogLayout
  title="How to Convert Audio to Text Free — 5 Best Methods"
  description="Learn how to convert audio recordings, voice memos, or video files to text for free. Covers Google Docs Voice Typing, YouTube captions, Otter.ai, and OpenAI Whisper."
  canonical="/blog/how-to-convert-audio-to-text"
  date="2026-06-23"
  readTime="6 min read"
  category="Productivity Guide"
  faqs={faqs}
>

<p>
  Converting audio to text — also called transcription — is useful for meetings, interviews, podcasts, lectures, and voice memos. Whether you need it done in real time or by uploading a file, there are several free and low-cost ways to do it. Here are the best methods available today.
</p>

<h2>Method 1: Google Docs Voice Typing (Free, Real-Time)</h2>

<p>
  Google Docs has a built-in <strong>Voice Typing</strong> feature that transcribes speech from your microphone in real time. It is completely free and requires only a Google account.
</p>

<ol>
  <li>Open <a href="https://docs.google.com" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Google Docs</a> and create a new document.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>Tools → Voice Typing</strong> (or press Ctrl+Shift+S).</li>
  <li>A microphone icon appears. Click it to start recording.</li>
  <li>Speak or play your audio near the microphone — Google transcribes it in real time.</li>
  <li>Click the microphone again to stop.</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Short audio, live meetings, dictating notes. Not ideal for pre-recorded audio files.</p>

<h2>Method 2: YouTube Auto-Captions (Free, Audio/Video Files)</h2>

<p>
  YouTube automatically transcribes any video you upload. You can use this to transcribe audio files too:
</p>

<ol>
  <li>Upload your audio or video file to YouTube as <strong>Unlisted</strong> (so only you can see it).</li>
  <li>Wait a few minutes — YouTube generates automatic captions.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>YouTube Studio → Subtitles → your video → Auto-generated captions.</strong></li>
  <li>Click the three-dot menu and choose <strong>Download</strong> (.srt or .vtt format) — or open the transcript and copy the text.</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Audio and video files up to 15 hours. Free and surprisingly accurate for clear speech.</p>

<h2>Method 3: Otter.ai (Best Free Tier for Upload)</h2>

<p>
  <a href="https://otter.ai" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Otter.ai</a> is a dedicated transcription service with a free tier that allows importing audio files:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Free plan:</strong> 300 minutes of transcription per month, 3 audio imports per month.</li>
  <li>Supports MP3, MP4, WAV, M4A formats.</li>
  <li>Generates a searchable transcript with speaker labels.</li>
  <li>Export as .txt or .docx.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Meeting recordings, interviews, and anything under 300 minutes per month where you want a clean, searchable transcript.</p>

<h2>Method 4: OpenAI Whisper (Free, Offline, Most Accurate)</h2>

<p>
  <strong>Whisper</strong> is an open-source speech-to-text model released by OpenAI. It runs entirely on your computer (no internet required after download) and is widely considered the most accurate free transcription tool available.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Supports 99 languages.</li>
  <li>Works with audio and video files (MP3, WAV, MP4, M4A, etc.).</li>
  <li>Completely free and private — nothing leaves your device.</li>
  <li>Requires Python and a terminal to run.</li>
</ul>

<p>Basic usage:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Install Python and run: <code>pip install openai-whisper</code></li>
  <li>Run: <code>whisper your-audio-file.mp3 --language English</code></li>
  <li>Whisper saves the transcript as .txt, .srt, and .vtt files in the same folder.</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Anyone comfortable with the command line who needs accurate transcription of longer recordings.</p>

<h2>Method 5: Microsoft Word Dictate (Free, Real-Time)</h2>

<p>
  Microsoft Word (Microsoft 365) has a built-in <strong>Dictate</strong> feature similar to Google Docs Voice Typing:
</p>
<ol>
  <li>Open Word online or the desktop app.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>Home → Dictate.</strong></li>
  <li>Click the microphone and speak or play audio near your microphone.</li>
  <li>Word transcribes in real time.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Comparison: Which Tool to Choose?</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Real-time, free:</strong> Google Docs Voice Typing or Microsoft Word Dictate</li>
  <li><strong>Upload a file, free:</strong> YouTube auto-captions or Otter.ai (free tier)</li>
  <li><strong>Best accuracy, fully offline:</strong> OpenAI Whisper</li>
  <li><strong>Best paid option:</strong> Otter.ai Pro, Rev, or Descript for professional transcription</li>
</ul>

